            "new_string": "    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <div class=\"callout callout-info\">\n        <div class=\"callout-icon\">→</div>\n        <div class=\"callout-content\">\n          <strong class=\"callout-title\">One more phase to go: Memory &amp; Skills</strong>\n          <p>You've mastered context management. Next up: Phase 7 — persistent agent memory, skill discovery, and the cross-thread store that makes state survive model switches.</p>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!-- ==================== MODULE 10: Memory & Skills ==================== -->\n<section class=\"module\" id=\"module-10\">\n  <div class=\"module-content\">\n    <header class=\"module-header animate-in\">\n      <span class=\"module-number\">10</span>\n      <h1 class=\"module-title\">Memory &amp; Skills</h1>\n      <p class=\"module-subtitle\">AGENTS.md persistence, skill discovery, and the InMemoryStore — Phase 7</p>\n    </header>\n\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen-heading\">Two-level configuration hierarchy</h2>\n      <p style=\"margin-bottom: var(--space-6);\">Phase 7 introduces two kinds of persisted data the agent can read before answering. Both follow the same <strong>user-level → project-level</strong> pattern:</p>\n      <div class=\"pattern-cards stagger-children\">\n        <div class=\"pattern-card animate-in\" style=\"--stagger-index: 0; border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-2)\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-2)\">🧠</div>\n          <h4 class=\"pattern-title\">Memory — AGENTS.md</h4>\n          <p class=\"pattern-desc\">Markdown files the agent reads as background context. Checked at <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">~/.deepagents/AGENTS.md</code> (user-wide) and <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">.deepagents/AGENTS.md</code> (per-project). Put facts, preferences, or standing instructions here.</p>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card animate-in\" style=\"--stagger-index: 1; border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-3)\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-3)\">⚡</div>\n          <h4 class=\"pattern-title\">Skills — .md files in skills/</h4>\n          <p class=\"pattern-desc\">Reusable prompt-snippets the agent can invoke by name. Discovered in <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">~/.deepagents/skills/</code> and <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">.deepagents/skills/</code>. Each <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">.md</code> file = one skill, named after its stem.</p>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout callout-info\" style=\"margin-top: var(--space-6)\">\n        <div class=\"callout-icon\">📌</div>\n        <div class=\"callout-content\">\n          <strong class=\"callout-title\">User-level loads first</strong>\n          <p>Both <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">get_memory_sources()</code> and <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">get_skill_sources()</code> return user-level paths before project-level paths. When the same skill name appears in both, the project-level file wins — later entries in the list take precedence.</p>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen-heading\">How skills are discovered</h2>\n      <p style=\"margin-bottom: var(--space-6);\"><code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">list_available_skills(sources)</code> scans each directory non-recursively for <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">.md</code> files and extracts two fields:</p>\n      <div class=\"step-cards stagger-children\">\n        <div class=\"step-card animate-in\" style=\"--stagger-index: 0\">\n          <div class=\"step-num\">1</div>\n          <div class=\"step-body\">\n            <strong>name — the filename stem</strong>\n            <p><code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">web-search.md</code> → <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">{\"name\": \"web-search\"}</code>. Simple, no parsing required.</p>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"step-card animate-in\" style=\"--stagger-index: 1\">\n          <div class=\"step-num\">2</div>\n          <div class=\"step-body\">\n            <strong>description — first non-heading, non-empty line</strong>\n            <p>Lines starting with <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">#</code> are skipped. Empty lines are skipped. The first line that survives both checks is stripped and used as the description. If the whole file is headings, description is <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">\"\"</code>.</p>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"step-card animate-in\" style=\"--stagger-index: 2\">\n          <div class=\"step-num\">3</div>\n          <div class=\"step-body\">\n            <strong>Sorted by name, unreadable files silently skipped</strong>\n            <p>The final list is alphabetical. <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">OSError</code> (permission denied, missing) and <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">ValueError</code> (bad encoding) are caught per-file — one bad skill doesn't break the rest.</p>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout callout-accent\" style=\"margin-top: var(--space-4)\">\n        <div class=\"callout-icon\">⚠️</div>\n        <div class=\"callout-content\">\n          <strong class=\"callout-title\">POSIX strings, not Path objects</strong>\n          <p>Both source functions return strings like <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">\"~/.deepagents/skills\"</code> and <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">\".deepagents/skills\"</code> — not <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">Path</code> objects. This keeps the display-facing keys consistent (no <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">./ </code> prefix) while callers use <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">Path(s).expanduser().resolve()</code> when they need an absolute path.</p>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen-heading\">The InMemoryStore — state that survives model switches</h2>\n      <p style=\"margin-bottom: var(--space-6);\"><code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">create_store()</code> in <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">backend.py</code> returns a LangGraph <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">InMemoryStore</code>. The adapter holds one instance for its entire lifetime:</p>\n      <div class=\"icon-rows\">\n        <div class=\"icon-row animate-in\">\n          <div class=\"icon-circle\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-2)\">🔒</div>\n          <div>\n            <strong>Lazy import in <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">create_store()</code></strong>\n            <p>The <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">from langgraph.store.memory import InMemoryStore</code> lives inside the function body. DeepAgents not installed? The function is never called — no import error at startup.</p>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"icon-row animate-in\">\n          <div class=\"icon-circle\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-3)\">♻️</div>\n          <div>\n            <strong><code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">if self._store is None</code> guard</strong>\n            <p>The store is created once on the first call to <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">_ensure_agent()</code> and reused forever. Calling <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">/model</code> to switch models clears <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">self._agent</code> but not <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">self._store</code> — cross-thread state survives the switch.</p>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"icon-row animate-in\">\n          <div class=\"icon-circle\" style=\"background: var(--color-success)\">✓</div>\n          <div>\n            <strong>Passed to <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">create_deep_agent(store=…)</code></strong>\n            <p>Alongside <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">memory=</code> (AGENTS.md paths) and <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">skills=</code> (skill directory paths), the store gives the agent a place to persist structured data across conversation threads.</p>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen-heading\">The /skills and /memory commands</h2>\n      <p style=\"margin-bottom: var(--space-6);\">Phase 7 surfaces memory and skills to the user via two slash commands:</p>\n      <div class=\"pattern-cards stagger-children\">\n        <div class=\"pattern-card animate-in\" style=\"--stagger-index: 0; border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-3)\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-3)\">⚡</div>\n          <h4 class=\"pattern-title\">/skills</h4>\n          <p class=\"pattern-desc\">Reads <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">self._discovered_skills</code> — the merged cache already built at startup by <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">_discover_skills()</code>. No extra filesystem scan. Shows name and description for each skill, sorted alphabetically.</p>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"pattern-card animate-in\" style=\"--stagger-index: 1; border-top: 3px solid var(--color-actor-2)\">\n          <div class=\"pattern-icon\" style=\"background: var(--color-actor-2)\">🧠</div>\n          <h4 class=\"pattern-title\">/memory</h4>\n          <p class=\"pattern-desc\">Calls <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">get_memory_summary()</code> directly — no agent needed, no async call. Returns a human-readable string listing each source file and its line count, e.g. <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">~/.deepagents/AGENTS.md (42 lines)</code>.</p>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n      <div class=\"callout callout-info\" style=\"margin-top: var(--space-6)\">\n        <div class=\"callout-icon\">🔍</div>\n        <div class=\"callout-content\">\n          <strong class=\"callout-title\">/skills reads the cache, not the adapter</strong>\n          <p>Calling <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">self._agent.get_skills()</code> again would re-scan the filesystem and return only protocol-reported skills — missing anything found by the startup filesystem walk. Reading <code style=\"font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm)\">self._discovered_skills</code> is both faster and complete.</p>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"screen animate-in\">\n      <h2 class=\"screen-heading\">Quiz: Memory &amp; Skills</h2>\n      <div class=\"quiz-container\" id=\"quiz-10\">\n        <div class=\"quiz-question-bl